rantReference>RES-072-27-0027</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The issues of rural incomes, employment, and socio-economic class relations and inequality have taken on a special significance in India over the last 15 years, when the impact of new economic policies on India's countryside has become a matter of much scholarly debate and crucial socio-political concern. The cutting edge of scholarly work on incomes and employment has, however, been blunted by the absence of published sources of data on rural household incomes and on patterns of rural employment in India. Thus, rural income-poverty studies are based on household consumer expenditure surveys rather than on direct computations of household incomes, while studies of patterns of rural agricultural and non-agricultural employment are not conducted in any rigorous way at all. The proposed research seeks to remedy this shortcoming by using primary data on household income and employment collected from three villages in the state of Andhra Pradesh. A study of rural incomes and employment in the post-reform period has particular relevance in Andhra Pradesh as this state came to be known for an active programme of liberalisation in the 1990s. The study will thus contribute towards understanding the impact of economic liberalisation on poverty and inequality in rural India.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>5374</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><